I prefer having member functions that convert to a different value, and friend functions that create instances from another type:<p><pre><code>    Distance d = feet(7);
    d += meters(3);
    std::cout << d.yards();

    Distance d2 = 3; // I won&#x27;t compile
</code></pre>
This assumes that you <i>want to</i> mix units, not defeat it. It all ends up being very efficient; use MKS for the underlying representation. You can multiply, add, and so on, quite efficiently; the only conversions happen on input and output.
